However, in recent years, Mexico has seen a significant cultural shift. In 2021, the "Ley anti-chancla" (the anti-spanking law) was implemented nationwide, formally prohibiting the use of physical force or humiliating treatment as a form of discipline. This change reflects a growing societal consensus—promoted by human rights organizations and modern child development experts—that violence is not an appropriate educational tool. While some traditional views persist in certain circles, the contemporary national value emphasizes the protection of the child's integrity and the rejection of physical punishment.

